 make them faster to download and then they're translated to either a binhex or MacBinary format that other computers can The Macintosh uses a special two fork filing system that chokes most other BinHex files are bit ASCII text files while MacBinary files are pure bit binary data that must always be transferred using a binary How a file has been translated and compressed for transmission is indicated by its Normally a file will have a name something like indicates how it was compressed and indicates how it was To use a file you've FTP'd and downloaded to your Mac you'll need to reverse the Most files you get from the net require a two step decoding First change the binhex or MacBinary file to a double clickable Macintosh file then decompress Which programs decode which file types is covered in the table Also note that most Macintosh telecommunications programs will automatically convert MacBinary files to regular Macintosh files as they are Suffix Extractors StuffIt X X X X X Compact Pro X X Packit X UUTool X MacCompress X SunTar X X X X BinHex X BinHex X DiskDoubler X X UnZip X DiskCopy X macutil X X X X A few notes on the decompressors StuffIt is a family of products that use several different compression The freeware StuffIt Expander will unstuff all of Versions of StuffIt earlier than StuffIt StuffIt Classic UnStuffIt and StuffIt Deluxe and will not unstuff the increasing number of files stuffed by StuffIt You need to get a more recent version of StuffIt or StuffIt StuffIt Lite and Deluxe consistently makes smaller archives than any other Macintosh compression To allow maximum space for files on the various ftp sites and to keep net bandwidth down please compress all files you send to anonymous ftp sites with StuffIt UUTool MacCompress and SunTar handle the popular UNIX formats of uuencode compress and tar The UNIX versions are often more robust than the Mac products so use them instead when that's an Translators that allow StuffIt Lite to expand uuencoded and tar files are also available by anonymous Macutil is dik winter's package of UNIX utilities to decompress and debinhex files on a workstation before downloading them to a Since UNIX stores files differently than does the Mac macutil creates MacBinary files which should be automatically converted on It can't decompress In particular it can't decompress the new StuffIt However if you need only one or two files out of an archive for instance if you want to read the README to find out if a program does what you need it to do before you download all of it macutil is It can be found at sumex aim in the info mac unix A few notes on the compression formats These are MacBinary Always use a binary file transfer protocol when transferring them never ASCII or Most files on the net are stored as Only rascal stores most of its files in Most communications programs such as ZTerm and MacKermit are capable of translating MacBinary files on the fly as they download if they know in advance they'll be downloading MacBinary This format is normally used only for system software so that on line users can download files that can easily be converted into exact copies of the installer Instead of using DiskCopy to restore the images to floppies you can use Steve Christensen's freeware utility MountImage to treat the images on your hard disk as actual floppies inserted in a floppy MountImage has a reputation for being buggy so you should have some blank floppies and a copy of DiskCopy handy just in files don't merit a position in the above table because they're self They may have been created with Compact Pro StuffIt or even DiskDoubler but all should be capable of decompressing themselves when double For some unknown reason Alysis has chosen not to use this industry standard designation for self extracting archives created with their payware products SuperDisk and More Disk Instead they append either or to self extracting HOW CAN I GET BINHEX STUFFIT By far the easiest way to get these progra